#: ../../../environments.rst:-1
msgid ""
"Learn how to use Spack environments to manage reproducible software stacks, "
"making it easy to share and recreate specific sets of packages and their "
"dependencies."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:13
msgid "Environments (spack.yaml, spack.lock)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:15
msgid ""
"An environment is used to group a set of specs intended for some purpose to "
"be built, rebuilt, and deployed in a coherent fashion. Environments define "
"aspects of the installation of the software, such as:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:18
msgid "*which* specs to install;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:19
msgid "*how* those specs are configured; and"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:20
msgid "*where* the concretized software will be installed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:22
msgid ""
"Aggregating this information into an environment for processing has "
"advantages over the *à la carte* approach of building and loading individual "
"Spack modules."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:24
msgid ""
"With environments, you concretize, install, or load (activate) all of the "
"specs with a single command. Concretization fully configures the specs and "
"dependencies of the environment in preparation for installing the software. "
"This is a more robust solution than ad-hoc installation scripts. And you can "
"share an environment or even re-use it on a different computer."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:29
msgid ""
"Environment definitions, especially *how* specs are configured, allow the "
"software to remain stable and repeatable even when Spack packages are "
"upgraded. Changes are only picked up when the environment is explicitly re-"
"concretized."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:32
msgid ""
"Defining *where* specs are installed supports a filesystem view of the "
"environment. Yet Spack maintains a single installation of the software that "
"can be re-used across multiple environments."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:35
msgid ""
"Activating an environment determines *when* all of the associated (and "
"installed) specs are loaded so limits the software loaded to those specs "
"actually needed by the environment. Spack can even generate a script to load "
"all modules related to an environment."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:38
msgid ""
"Other packaging systems also provide environments that are similar in some "
"ways to Spack environments; for example, `Conda environments <https://conda."
"io/docs/user-guide/tasks/manage-environments.html>`_ or `Python Virtual "
"Environments <https://docs.python.org/3/tutorial/venv.html>`_. Spack "
"environments provide some distinctive features though:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:41
msgid ""
"A spec installed \"in\" an environment is no different from the same spec "
"installed anywhere else in Spack."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:42
msgid "Spack environments may contain more than one spec of the same package."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:44
msgid ""
"Spack uses a \"manifest and lock\" model similar to `Bundler gemfiles "
"<https://bundler.io/man/gemfile.5.html>`_ and other package managers. The "
"environment's user input file (or manifest), is named ``spack.yaml``. The "
"lock file, which contains the fully configured and concretized specs, is "
"named ``spack.lock``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:51
msgid "Using Environments"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:53
msgid ""
"Here we follow a typical use case of creating, concretizing, installing and "
"loading an environment."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:58
msgid "Creating a managed Environment"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:60
msgid "An environment is created by:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:62
msgid "$ spack env create myenv"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:66
msgid ""
"The directory ``$SPACK_ROOT/var/spack/environments/myenv`` is created to "
"manage the environment."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:70
msgid ""
"By default, all managed environments are stored in the ``$SPACK_ROOT/var/"
"spack/environments`` folder. This location can be changed by setting the "
"``environments_root`` variable in ``config.yaml``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:73
msgid ""
"Spack creates the file ``spack.yaml``, hidden directory ``.spack-env``, and "
"``spack.lock`` file under ``$SPACK_ROOT/var/spack/environments/myenv``. User "
"interaction occurs through the ``spack.yaml`` file and the Spack commands "
"that affect it. Metadata and, by default, the view are stored in the ``."
"spack-env`` directory. When the environment is concretized, Spack creates "
"the ``spack.lock`` file with the fully configured specs and dependencies for "
"the environment."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:78
msgid "The ``.spack-env`` subdirectory also contains:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:80
msgid ""
"``repo/``: A subdirectory acting as the repo consisting of the Spack "
"packages used in the environment. It allows the environment to build the "
"same, in theory, even on different versions of Spack with different packages!"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:82
msgid ""
"``logs/``: A subdirectory containing the build logs for the packages in this "
"environment."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:84
msgid ""
"Spack Environments can also be created from another environment. "
"Environments can be created from the manifest file (the user input), the "
"lockfile, or the entire environment at once. Create an environment from a "
"manifest using:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:88
msgid "$ spack env create myenv spack.yaml"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:92
msgid ""
"The resulting environment is guaranteed to have the same root specs as the "
"original but may concretize differently in the presence of different "
"explicit or default configuration settings (e.g., a different version of "
"Spack or for a different user account)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:94
msgid ""
"Environments created from a manifest will copy any included configs from "
"relative paths inside the environment. Relative paths from outside the "
"environment will cause errors, and absolute paths will be kept absolute. For "
"example, if ``spack.yaml`` includes:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:98
msgid ""
"spack:\n"
"  include: [./config.yaml]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:103
msgid ""
"then the created environment will have its own copy of the file ``config."
"yaml`` copied from the location in the original environment."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:105
msgid "Create an environment from a ``spack.lock`` file using:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:107
msgid "$ spack env create myenv spack.lock"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:111
msgid ""
"The resulting environment, when on the same or a compatible machine, is "
"guaranteed to initially have the same concrete specs as the original."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:113
msgid ""
"Create an environment from an entire environment using either the "
"environment name or path:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:115
msgid ""
"$ spack env create myenv /path/to/env\n"
"$ spack env create myenv2 myenv"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:120
msgid ""
"The resulting environment will include the concrete specs from the original "
"if the original is concretized (as when created from a lockfile) and all of "
"the config options and abstract specs specified in the original (as when "
"created from a manifest file). It will also include any other files included "
"in the environment directory, such as repos or source code, as they could be "
"referenced in the environment by relative path."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:125
msgid "Environment creation also accepts a full path to the file."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:127
msgid ""
"If the path is not under the ``$SPACK_ROOT/var/spack/environments`` "
"directory then the source is referred to as an :ref:`independent environment "
"<independent_environments>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:129
msgid ""
"The name of an environment can be a nested path to help organize "
"environments via subdirectories."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:131
msgid "$ spack env create projectA/configA/myenv"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:135
msgid ""
"This will create a managed environment under ``$environments_root/projectA/"
"configA/myenv``. Changing ``environment_root`` can therefore also be used to "
"make a whole group of nested environments available."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:142
msgid "Activating an Environment"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:144
msgid "To activate an environment, use the following command:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:146
msgid "$ spack env activate myenv"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:150
msgid ""
"By default, the ``spack env activate`` will load the view associated with "
"the environment into the user environment. The ``-v, --with-view`` argument "
"ensures this behavior, and the ``-V, --without-view`` argument activates the "
"environment without changing the user environment variables."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:153
msgid ""
"The ``-p`` option to the ``spack env activate`` command modifies the user's "
"prompt to begin with the environment name in brackets."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:155
msgid ""
"$ spack env activate -p myenv\n"
"[myenv] $ ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:160
msgid ""
"The ``activate`` command can also be used to create a new environment, if it "
"is not already defined, by adding the ``--create`` flag. Managed and "
"independent environments can both be created using the same flags that "
"`spack env create` accepts. If an environment already exists then Spack will "
"simply activate it and ignore the create-specific flags."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:164
msgid ""
"$ spack env activate --create -p myenv\n"
"# ...\n"
"# [creates if myenv does not exist yet]\n"
"# ...\n"
"[myenv] $ ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:172
msgid "To deactivate an environment, use the command:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:174
msgid "$ spack env deactivate"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:178
msgid "or the shortcut alias"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:180
msgid "$ despacktivate"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:184
msgid ""
"If the environment was activated with its view, deactivating the environment "
"will remove the view from the user environment."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:189
msgid "Independent Environments"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:191
msgid ""
"Independent environments can be located in any directory outside of Spack."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:195
msgid ""
"When uninstalling packages, Spack asks the user to confirm the removal of "
"packages that are still used in a managed environment. This is not the case "
"for independent environments."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:198
msgid ""
"To create an independent environment, use one of the following commands:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:200
msgid ""
"$ spack env create --dir my_env\n"
"$ spack env create ./my_env"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:205
msgid ""
"As a shorthand, you can also create an independent environment upon "
"activation if it does not already exist:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:207
msgid "$ spack env activate --create ./my_env"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:211
msgid ""
"For convenience, Spack can also place an independent environment in a "
"temporary directory for you:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:213
msgid "$ spack env activate --temp"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:219
msgid "Environment-Aware Commands"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:221
msgid ""
"Spack commands are environment-aware. For example, the ``find`` command "
"shows only the specs in the active environment if an environment has been "
"activated. Otherwise it shows all specs in the Spack instance. The same rule "
"applies to the ``install`` and ``uninstall`` commands."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:226
msgid ""
"$ spack find\n"
"==> 0 installed packages\n"
"\n"
"$ spack install zlib@1.2.11\n"
"[+] q6cqrdt zlib@1.2.11 ~/spack/opt/spack/linux-rhel7-broadwell/gcc-8.1.0/"
"zlib-1.2.11-q6cqrdto4iktfg6qyqcc5u4vmfmwb7iv (12s)\n"
"\n"
"$ spack env activate myenv\n"
"\n"
"$ spack find\n"
"==> In environment myenv\n"
"==> No root specs\n"
"==> 0 installed packages\n"
"\n"
"$ spack install zlib@1.2.8\n"
"[+] yfc7epf zlib@1.2.8 ~/spack/opt/spack/linux-rhel7-broadwell/gcc-8.1.0/"
"zlib-1.2.8-yfc7epf57nsfn2gn4notccaiyxha6z7x (12s)\n"
"==> Updating view at ~/spack/var/spack/environments/myenv/.spack-env/view\n"
"\n"
"$ spack find\n"
"==> In environment myenv\n"
"==> Root specs\n"
"zlib@1.2.8\n"
"\n"
"==> 1 installed package\n"
"-- linux-rhel7-broadwell / gcc@8.1.0 ----------------------------\n"
"zlib@1.2.8\n"
"\n"
"$ despacktivate\n"
"\n"
"$ spack find\n"
"==> 2 installed packages\n"
"-- linux-rhel7-broadwell / gcc@8.1.0 ----------------------------\n"
"zlib@1.2.8  zlib@1.2.11"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:262
msgid ""
"Note that when we installed the abstract spec ``zlib@1.2.8``, it was "
"presented as a root of the environment. All explicitly installed packages "
"will be listed as roots of the environment."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:265
msgid ""
"All of the Spack commands that act on the list of installed specs are "
"environment-aware in this way, including ``install``, ``uninstall``, "
"``find``, ``extensions``, etc. In the :ref:`environment-configuration` "
"section we will discuss environment-aware commands further."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:271
msgid "Adding Abstract Specs"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:273
msgid ""
"An abstract spec is the user-specified spec before Spack applies defaults or "
"dependency information."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:275
msgid ""
"You can add abstract specs to an environment using the ``spack add`` "
"command. This adds the abstract spec as a root of the environment in the "
"``spack.yaml`` file. The most important component of an environment is a "
"list of abstract specs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:279
msgid ""
"Adding abstract specs does not immediately install anything, nor does it "
"affect the ``spack.lock`` file. To update the lockfile, the environment must "
"be :ref:`re-concretized <cmd-spack-concretize>`, and to update any "
"installations, the environment must be :ref:`(re)installed <installing-"
"environment>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:282
msgid ""
"The ``spack add`` command is environment-aware. It adds the spec to the "
"currently active environment. An error is generated if there isn't an active "
"environment."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:286
msgid ""
"$ spack env activate myenv\n"
"$ spack add mpileaks"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:291
msgid "or"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:293
msgid "$ spack -e myenv add python"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:299
msgid ""
"All environment-aware commands can also be called using the ``spack -e`` "
"flag to specify the environment."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:304
msgid "Concretizing"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:306
msgid ""
"Once user specs have been added to an environment, they can be concretized. "
"There are three different modes of operation to concretize an environment, "
"explained in detail in :ref:`environments_concretization_config`. Regardless "
"of which mode of operation is chosen, the following command will ensure all "
"of the root specs are concretized according to the constraints that are "
"prescribed in the configuration:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:310
msgid "[myenv]$ spack concretize"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:314
msgid ""
"In the case of specs that are not concretized together, the command above "
"will concretize only the specs that were added and not yet concretized. "
"Forcing a re-concretization of all of the specs can be done by adding the ``-"
"f`` option:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:317
msgid "[myenv]$ spack concretize -f"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:321
msgid ""
"Without the option, Spack guarantees that already concretized specs are "
"unchanged in the environment."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:323
msgid ""
"The ``concretize`` command does not install any packages. For packages that "
"have already been installed outside of the environment, the process of "
"adding the spec and concretizing is identical to installing the spec "
"assuming it concretizes to the exact spec that was installed outside of the "
"environment."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:326
msgid ""
"The ``spack find`` command can show concretized specs separately from "
"installed specs using the ``-c`` (``--concretized``) flag."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:328
msgid ""
"[myenv]$ spack add zlib\n"
"[myenv]$ spack concretize\n"
"[myenv]$ spack find -c\n"
"==> In environment myenv\n"
"==> Root specs\n"
"zlib\n"
"\n"
"==> Concretized roots\n"
"-- linux-rhel7-x86_64 / gcc@4.9.3 -------------------------------\n"
"zlib@1.2.11\n"
"\n"
"==> 0 installed packages"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:347
msgid "Installing an Environment"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:349
msgid ""
"In addition to adding individual specs to an environment, one can install "
"the entire environment at once using the command"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:351
msgid "[myenv]$ spack install"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:355
msgid ""
"If the environment has been concretized, Spack will install the concretized "
"specs. Otherwise, ``spack install`` will concretize the environment before "
"installing the concretized specs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:360
msgid ""
"Every ``spack install`` process builds one package at a time with multiple "
"build jobs, controlled by the ``-j`` flag and the ``config:build_jobs`` "
"option (see :ref:`build-jobs`). To speed up environment builds further, "
"independent packages can be installed in parallel by launching more Spack "
"instances. For example, the following will build at most four packages in "
"parallel using three background jobs:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:364
msgid "[myenv]$ spack install & spack install & spack install & spack install"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:368
msgid ""
"Another option is to generate a ``Makefile`` and run ``make -j<N>`` to "
"control the number of parallel install processes. See :ref:`cmd-spack-env-"
"depfile` for details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:372
msgid ""
"As it installs, ``spack install`` creates symbolic links in the ``logs/`` "
"directory in the environment, allowing for easy inspection of build logs "
"related to that environment. The ``spack install`` command also stores a "
"Spack repo containing the ``package.py`` file used at install time for each "
"package in the ``repos/`` directory in the environment."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:375
msgid ""
"The ``--no-add`` option can be used in a concrete environment to tell Spack "
"to install specs already present in the environment but not to add any new "
"root specs to the environment. For root specs provided to ``spack install`` "
"on the command line, ``--no-add`` is the default, while for dependency "
"specs, it is optional. In other words, if there is an unambiguous match in "
"the active concrete environment for a root spec provided to ``spack "
"install`` on the command line, Spack does not require you to specify the ``--"
"no-add`` option to prevent the spec from being added again. At the same "
"time, a spec that already exists in the environment, but only as a "
"dependency, will be added to the environment as a root spec without the ``--"
"no-add`` option."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:383
msgid "Developing Packages in a Spack Environment"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:385
msgid ""
"The ``spack develop`` command allows one to develop Spack packages in an "
"environment. It will configure Spack to install the package from local "
"source. By default, ``spack develop`` will also clone the package to a "
"subdirectory in the environment for the local source. These choices can be "
"overridden with the ``--path`` argument, and the ``--no-clone`` argument. "
"Relative paths provided to the ``--path`` argument will be resolved relative "
"to the environment directory. All of these options are recorded in the "
"environment manifest, although default values may be left implied."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:392
msgid ""
"$ spack develop --path src/foo foo@develop\n"
"$ cat `spack location -e`/spack.yaml\n"
"spack:\n"
"  ...\n"
"  develop\n"
"    foo:\n"
"      spec: foo@develop\n"
"      path: src/foo"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:403
msgid ""
"When ``spack develop`` is run in a concretized environment, Spack will "
"modify the concrete specs in the environment to reflect the modified "
"provenance. Any package built from local source will have a ``dev_path`` "
"variant, and the hash of any dependent of those packages will be modified to "
"reflect the change. The value of the ``dev_path`` variant will be the "
"absolute path to the package source directory. If the develop spec conflicts "
"with the concrete specs in the environment, Spack will raise an exception "
"and require the ``spack develop --no-modify-concrete-specs`` option, "
"followed by a ``spack concretize --force`` to apply the ``dev_path`` variant "
"and constraints from the develop spec."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:408
msgid ""
"When concretizing an environment with develop specs, the version, variants, "
"and other attributes of the spec provided to the ``spack develop`` command "
"will be treated as constraints by the concretizer (in addition to any "
"constraints from the packages ``specs`` list). If the ``develop`` "
"configuration for the package does not include a spec version, Spack will "
"choose the **highest** version of the package. This means that any "
"\"infinity\" versions (``develop``, ``main``, etc.) will be preferred for "
"specs marked with the ``spack develop`` command, which is different from the "
"standard Spack behavior to prefer the highest **numeric** version. These "
"packages will have an automatic ``dev_path`` variant added by the "
"concretizer, with a value of the absolute path to the local source Spack is "
"building from."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:413
msgid ""
"Spack will ensure the package and its dependents are rebuilt any time the "
"environment is installed if the package's local source code has been "
"modified. Spack's native implementation is to check if ``mtime`` is newer "
"than the installation. A custom check can be created by overriding the "
"``detect_dev_src_change`` method in your package class. This is particularly "
"useful for projects using custom Spack repos to drive development and want "
"to optimize performance."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:418
msgid ""
"When ``spack develop`` is run without any arguments, Spack will clone any "
"develop specs in the environment for which the specified path does not exist."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:420
msgid ""
"When working deep in the graph it is often desirable to have multiple specs "
"marked as ``develop`` so you don't have to restage and/or do full rebuilds "
"each time you call ``spack install``. The ``--recursive`` flag can be used "
"in these scenarios to ensure that all the dependents of the initial spec you "
"provide are also marked as develop specs. The ``--recursive`` flag requires "
"a pre-concretized environment so the graph can be traversed from the "
"supplied spec all the way to the root specs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:424
msgid ""
"For packages with ``git`` attributes, git branches, tags, and commits can "
"also be used as valid concrete versions (see :ref:`version-specifier`). This "
"means that for a package ``foo``, ``spack develop foo@git.main`` will clone "
"the ``main`` branch of the package, and ``spack install`` will install from "
"that git clone if ``foo`` is in the environment. Further development on "
"``foo`` can be tested by re-installing the environment, and eventually "
"committed and pushed to the upstream git repo."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:428
msgid ""
"If the package being developed supports out-of-source builds then users can "
"use the ``--build_directory`` flag to control the location and name of the "
"build directory. This is a shortcut to set the ``package_attributes:"
"build_directory`` in the ``packages`` configuration (see :ref:`assigning-"
"package-attributes`). The supplied location will become the build-directory "
"for that package in all future builds."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:432
msgid "Potential pitfalls of setting the build directory"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:435
msgid ""
"Spack does not check for out-of-source build compatibility with the packages "
"and so the onus of making sure the package supports out-of-source builds is "
"on the user. For example, most ``autotool`` and ``makefile`` packages do not "
"support out-of-source builds while all ``CMake`` packages do. Understanding "
"these nuances is up to the software developers and we strongly encourage "
"developers to only redirect the build directory if they understand their "
"package's build-system."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:440
msgid "Modifying Specs in an Environment"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:442
msgid ""
"The ``spack change`` command allows the user to change individual specs in a "
"Spack environment."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:444
msgid ""
"By default, ``spack change`` operates on the abstract specs of an "
"environment. The command a list of spec arguments. For each argument, the "
"root spec with the same name as the provided spec is modified to satisfy the "
"provided spec. For example, in an environment with the root spec "
"``hdf5+mpi+fortran``, then"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:449
msgid "spack change hdf5~mpi+cxx"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:453
msgid "will change the root spec to ``hdf5~mpi+cxx+fortran``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:455
msgid ""
"When more complex matching semantics are necessary, the ``--match-spec`` "
"argument replaces the spec name as the selection criterion. When using the "
"``--match-spec`` argument, the spec name is not required. In the same "
"environment,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:459
msgid "spack change --match-spec \"+fortran\" +hl"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:463
msgid "will constrain the ``hdf5`` spec to ``+hl``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:465
msgid ""
"By default, the ``spack change`` command will result in an error and no "
"change to the environment if it will modify more than one abstract spec. Use "
"the ``--all`` option to allow ``spack change`` to modify multiple abstract "
"specs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:468
msgid ""
"The ``--concrete`` option allows ``spack change`` to modify the concrete "
"specs of an environment as well as the abstract specs. Multiple concrete "
"specs may be modified, even for a change that modifies only a single "
"abstract spec. The ``--all`` option does not affect how many concrete specs "
"may be modified."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:474
msgid ""
"Concrete specs are modified without any constraints from the packages. The "
"``spack change --concrete`` command  may create invalid specs that will not "
"build properly if applied without caution."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:477
msgid ""
"The ``--concrete-only`` option allows for modifying concrete specs without "
"modifying abstract specs. It allows changes to be applied to non-root nodes "
"in the environment, and other changes that do not modify any root specs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:481
msgid "Loading"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:483
msgid ""
"Once an environment has been installed, the following creates a load script "
"for it:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:485
msgid "$ spack env loads -r"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:489
msgid ""
"This creates a file called ``loads`` in the environment directory. Sourcing "
"that file in Bash will make the environment available to the user, and can "
"be included in ``.bashrc`` files, etc. The ``loads`` file may also be copied "
"out of the environment, renamed, etc."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:497
msgid "Including Concrete Environments"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:499
msgid ""
"Spack can create an environment that includes information from already "
"concretized environments. You can think of the new environment as a "
"combination of existing environments. It uses information from the existing "
"environments' ``spack.lock`` files in the creation of the new environment. "
"When such an environment is concretized it will generate its own ``spack."
"lock`` file that contains relevant information from the included "
"environments."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:506
msgid "Creating combined concrete environments"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:507
msgid ""
"To create a combined concrete environment, you must have at least one "
"existing concrete environment. You will use the command ``spack env create`` "
"with the argument ``--include-concrete`` followed by the name or path of the "
"environment you'd like to include. Here is an example of how to create a "
"combined environment from the command line::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:511
msgid ""
"$ spack env create myenv\n"
"$ spack -e myenv add python\n"
"$ spack -e myenv concretize\n"
"$ spack env create --include-concrete myenv combined_env"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:516
msgid ""
"You can also include concrete environments directly in the ``spack.yaml`` "
"file. It involves adding the absolute paths to the concrete environments "
"``spack.lock`` under the new environment's ``include`` heading. Spack-"
"specific configuration variables, such as ``$spack``, and environment "
"variables can be used in the include paths as long as the expression expands "
"to an absolute path. (See :ref:`config-file-variables` for more information.)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:521
msgid "For example,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:523
msgid ""
"spack:\n"
"  include:\n"
"  - /absolute/path/to/environment1/spack.lock\n"
"  - $spack/../path/to/environment2/spack.lock\n"
"  specs: []\n"
"  concretizer:\n"
"    unify: true"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:533
msgid ""
"will include the specs from ``environment1`` and ``environment2`` where the "
"second environment's path is the absolute path of the directory that is "
"relative to the spack root."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:537
msgid ""
"Once the ``spack.yaml`` file is updated you must concretize the new "
"environment to get the concrete specs from the included environments. This "
"will produce the combined ``spack.lock`` file."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:541
msgid "Updating a combined environment"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:542
msgid ""
"If you want changes made to one of the included environments reflected in "
"the combined environment, then you will need to re-concretize the included "
"environment **then** the combined environment for the change to be "
"incorporated. For example::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:545
msgid ""
"$ spack env create myenv\n"
"$ spack -e myenv add python\n"
"$ spack -e myenv concretize\n"
"$ spack env create --include-concrete myenv combined_env\n"
"\n"
"$ spack -e myenv find\n"
"==> In environment myenv\n"
"==> Root specs\n"
"python\n"
"\n"
"==> 0 installed packages\n"
"\n"
"$ spack -e combined_env find\n"
"==> In environment combined_env\n"
"==> No root specs\n"
"==> Included specs\n"
"python\n"
"\n"
"==> 0 installed packages"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:565
msgid ""
"Here we see that ``combined_env`` contains the python package from ``myenv`` "
"environment. But if we were to add another spec to ``myenv``, "
"``combined_env`` will not know about the other spec."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:568
msgid ""
"$ spack -e myenv add perl\n"
"$ spack -e myenv concretize\n"
"$ spack -e myenv find\n"
"==> In environment myenv\n"
"==> Root specs\n"
"perl  python\n"
"\n"
"==> 0 installed packages\n"
"\n"
"$ spack -e combined_env find\n"
"==> In environment combined_env\n"
"==> No root specs\n"
"==> Included specs\n"
"python\n"
"\n"
"==> 0 installed packages"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:587
msgid ""
"It isn't until you run the ``spack concretize`` command that the combined "
"environment will get the updated information from the re-concretized "
"``myenv``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:589
msgid ""
"$ spack -e combined_env concretize\n"
"$ spack -e combined_env find\n"
"==> In environment combined_env\n"
"==> No root specs\n"
"==> Included specs\n"
"perl  python\n"
"\n"
"==> 0 installed packages"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:603
msgid "Configuring Environments"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:605
msgid ""
"A variety of Spack behaviors are changed through Spack configuration files, "
"covered in more detail in the :ref:`configuration` section."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:607
msgid ""
"Spack Environments provide an additional level of configuration scope "
"between the custom scope and the user scope discussed in the configuration "
"documentation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:609
msgid ""
"There are two ways to include configuration information in a Spack "
"Environment:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:611
msgid "Inline in the ``spack.yaml`` file"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:613
msgid "Included in the ``spack.yaml`` file from another file."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:615
msgid ""
"Many Spack commands also affect configuration information in files "
"automatically. Those commands take a ``--scope`` argument, and the "
"environment can be specified by ``env:NAME`` (to affect environment ``foo``, "
"set ``--scope env:foo``). These commands will automatically manipulate "
"configuration inline in the ``spack.yaml`` file."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:620
msgid "Inline configurations"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:622
msgid ""
"Inline environment-scope configuration is done using the same yaml format as "
"standard Spack configuration scopes, covered in the :ref:`configuration` "
"section. Each section is contained under a top-level yaml object with its "
"name. For example, a ``spack.yaml`` manifest file containing some package "
"preference configuration (as in a ``packages.yaml`` file) could contain:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:626
msgid ""
"spack:\n"
"  # ...\n"
"  packages:\n"
"    all:\n"
"      providers:\n"
"        mpi: [openmpi]\n"
"  # ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:636
msgid "This configuration sets the default ``mpi`` provider to be ``openmpi``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:639
msgid "Included configurations"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:641
msgid ""
"Spack environments allow an ``include`` heading in their yaml schema. This "
"heading pulls in external configuration files and applies them to the "
"environment."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:644
msgid ""
"spack:\n"
"  include:\n"
"  - environment/relative/path/to/config.yaml\n"
"  - path: https://github.com/path/to/raw/config/compilers.yaml\n"
"    sha256: "
"26e871804a92cd07bb3d611b31b4156ae93d35b6a6d6e0ef3a67871fcb1d258b\n"
"  - /absolute/path/to/packages.yaml\n"
"  - path: /path/to/$os/$target/environment\n"
"    optional: true\n"
"  - path: /path/to/os-specific/config-dir\n"
"    when: os == \"ventura\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:657
msgid ""
"Included configuration files are required *unless* they are explicitly "
"optional or the entry's condition evaluates to ``false``. Optional includes "
"are specified with the ``optional`` clause and conditional with the ``when`` "
"clause. (See :ref:`include-yaml` for more information on optional and "
"conditional entries.)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:661
msgid ""
"Files are listed using paths to individual files or directories containing "
"them. Path entries may be absolute or relative to the environment or "
"specified as URLs. URLs to individual files must link to the **raw** form of "
"the file's contents (e.g., `GitHub <https://docs.github.com/en/repositories/"
"working-with-files/using-files/viewing-and-understanding-files#viewing-or-"
"copying-the-raw-file-content>`_ or `GitLab <https://docs.gitlab.com/ee/api/"
"repository_files.html#get-raw-file-from-repository>`_) **and** include a "
"valid sha256 for the file. Only the ``file``, ``ftp``, ``http`` and "
"``https`` protocols (or schemes) are supported. Spack-specific, environment "
"and user path variables can be used. (See :ref:`config-file-variables` for "
"more information.)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:670
msgid ""
"Recursive includes are not currently processed in a breadth-first manner so "
"the value of a configuration option that is altered by multiple included "
"files may not be what you expect. This will be addressed in a future update."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:675
msgid "Configuration precedence"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:677
msgid ""
"Inline configurations take precedence over included configurations, so you "
"don't have to change shared configuration files to make small changes to an "
"individual environment. Included configurations listed earlier will have "
"higher precedence, as the included configs are applied in reverse order."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:681
msgid "Manually Editing the Specs List"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:683
msgid ""
"The list of abstract/root specs in the environment is maintained in the "
"``spack.yaml`` manifest under the heading ``specs``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:685
msgid ""
"spack:\n"
"  specs:\n"
"  - ncview\n"
"  - netcdf\n"
"  - nco\n"
"  - py-sphinx"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:694
msgid ""
"Appending to this list in the yaml is identical to using the ``spack add`` "
"command from the command line. However, there is more power available from "
"the yaml file."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:700
msgid "Spec concretization"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:701
msgid ""
"An environment can be concretized in three different modes and the behavior "
"active under any environment is determined by the ``concretizer:unify`` "
"configuration option."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:703
msgid "The *default* mode is to unify all specs:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:705
msgid ""
"spack:\n"
"  specs:\n"
"  - hdf5+mpi\n"
"  - zlib@1.2.8\n"
"  concretizer:\n"
"    unify: true"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:714
msgid ""
"This means that any package in the environment corresponds to a single "
"concrete spec. In the above example, when ``hdf5`` depends down the line of "
"``zlib``, it is required to take ``zlib@1.2.8`` instead of a newer version. "
"This mode of concretization is particularly useful when environment views "
"are used: if every package occurs in only one flavor, it is usually possible "
"to merge all install directories into a view."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:718
msgid ""
"A downside of unified concretization is that it can be overly strict. For "
"example, a concretization error would happen when both ``hdf5+mpi`` and "
"``hdf5~mpi`` are specified in an environment."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:721
msgid ""
"The second mode is to *unify when possible*: this makes concretization of "
"root specs more independent. Instead of requiring reuse of dependencies "
"across different root specs, it is only maximized:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:724
msgid ""
"spack:\n"
"  specs:\n"
"  - hdf5~mpi\n"
"  - hdf5+mpi\n"
"  - zlib@1.2.8\n"
"  concretizer:\n"
"    unify: when_possible"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:734
msgid ""
"This means that both ``hdf5`` installations will use ``zlib@1.2.8`` as a "
"dependency even if newer versions of that library are available."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:736
msgid ""
"The third mode of operation is to concretize root specs entirely "
"independently by disabling unified concretization:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:738
msgid ""
"spack:\n"
"  specs:\n"
"  - hdf5~mpi\n"
"  - hdf5+mpi\n"
"  - zlib@1.2.8\n"
"  concretizer:\n"
"    unify: false"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:748
msgid ""
"In this example ``hdf5`` is concretized separately, and does not consider "
"``zlib@1.2.8`` as a constraint or preference. Instead, it will take the "
"latest possible version."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:751
msgid ""
"The last two concretization options are typically useful for system "
"administrators and user support groups providing a large software stack for "
"their HPC center."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:755
msgid ""
"The ``concretizer:unify`` config option was introduced in Spack 0.18 to "
"replace the ``concretization`` property. For reference, ``concretization: "
"together`` is replaced by ``concretizer:unify:true``, and ``concretization: "
"separately`` is replaced by ``concretizer:unify:false``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:758
msgid "Re-concretization of user specs"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:760
msgid ""
"The ``spack concretize`` command without additional arguments will *not* "
"change any previously concretized specs. This may prevent it from finding a "
"solution when using ``unify: true``, and it may prevent it from finding a "
"minimal solution when using ``unify: when_possible``. You can force Spack to "
"ignore the existing concrete environment with ``spack concretize -f``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:767
msgid "Spec Matrices"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:769
msgid ""
"Entries in the ``specs`` list can be individual abstract specs or a spec "
"matrix."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:771
msgid ""
"A spec matrix is a yaml object containing multiple lists of specs, and "
"evaluates to the cross-product of those specs. Spec matrices also contain an "
"``excludes`` directive, which eliminates certain combinations from the "
"evaluated result."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:774
msgid "The following two environment manifests are identical:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:776
msgid ""
"spack:\n"
"  specs:\n"
"  - zlib %gcc@7.1.0\n"
"  - zlib %gcc@4.9.3\n"
"  - libelf %gcc@7.1.0\n"
"  - libelf %gcc@4.9.3\n"
"  - libdwarf %gcc@7.1.0\n"
"  - cmake"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:787
msgid ""
"spack:\n"
"  specs:\n"
"  - matrix:\n"
"    - [zlib, libelf, libdwarf]\n"
"    - [\"%gcc@7.1.0\", \"%gcc@4.9.3\"]\n"
"    exclude:\n"
"    - libdwarf%gcc@4.9.3\n"
"  - cmake"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:798
msgid ""
"Spec matrices can be used to install swaths of software across various "
"toolchains."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:803
msgid "Spec List References"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:805
msgid "The last type of possible entry in the specs list is a reference."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:807
msgid ""
"The Spack Environment manifest yaml schema contains an additional heading "
"``definitions``. Under definitions is an array of yaml objects. Each object "
"has one or two fields. The one required field is a name, and the optional "
"field is a ``when`` clause."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:812
msgid ""
"The named field is a spec list. The spec list uses the same syntax as the "
"``specs`` entry. Each entry in the spec list can be a spec, a spec matrix, "
"or a reference to an earlier named list. References are specified using the "
"``$`` sigil, and are \"splatted\" into place (i.e. the elements of the "
"referent are at the same level as the elements listed separately). As an "
"example, the following two manifest files are identical."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:818
msgid ""
"spack:\n"
"  definitions:\n"
"  - first: [libelf, libdwarf]\n"
"  - compilers: [\"%gcc\", \"%intel\"]\n"
"  - second:\n"
"    - $first\n"
"    - matrix:\n"
"      - [zlib]\n"
"      - [$compilers]\n"
"  specs:\n"
"  - $second\n"
"  - cmake"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:833
msgid ""
"spack:\n"
"  specs:\n"
"  - libelf\n"
"  - libdwarf\n"
"  - zlib%gcc\n"
"  - zlib%intel\n"
"  - cmake"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:845
msgid ""
"Named spec lists in the definitions section may only refer to a named list "
"defined above itself. Order matters."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:848
msgid ""
"In short files like the example, it may be easier to simply list the "
"included specs. However for more complicated examples involving many "
"packages across many toolchains, separately factored lists make environments "
"substantially more manageable."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:851
msgid ""
"Additionally, the ``-l`` option to the ``spack add`` command allows one to "
"add to named lists in the definitions section of the manifest file directly "
"from the command line."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:853
msgid ""
"The ``when`` directive can be used to conditionally add specs to a named "
"list. The ``when`` directive takes a string of Python code referring to a "
"restricted set of variables, and evaluates to a boolean. The specs listed "
"are appended to the named list if the ``when`` string evaluates to ``True``. "
"In the following snippet, the named list ``compilers`` is ``[\"%gcc\", "
"\"%clang\", \"%intel\"]`` on ``x86_64`` systems and ``[\"%gcc\", "
"\"%clang\"]`` on all other systems."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:858
msgid ""
"spack:\n"
"  definitions:\n"
"  - compilers: [\"%gcc\", \"%clang\"]\n"
"  - when: arch.satisfies(\"target=x86_64:\")\n"
"    compilers: [\"%intel\"]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:868
msgid ""
"Any definitions with the same named list with true ``when`` clauses (or "
"absent ``when`` clauses) will be appended together"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:870
msgid "The valid variables for a ``when`` clause are:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:872
msgid ""
"``platform``. The platform string of the default Spack architecture on the "
"system."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:875
msgid "``os``. The OS string of the default Spack architecture on the system."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:878
msgid ""
"``target``. The target string of the default Spack architecture on the "
"system."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:881
msgid ""
"``architecture`` or ``arch``. A Spack spec satisfying the default Spack "
"architecture on the system. This supports querying via the ``satisfies`` "
"method, as shown above."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:885
msgid ""
"``arch_str``. The architecture string of the default Spack architecture on "
"the system."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:888
msgid "``re``. The standard regex module in Python."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:891
msgid "``env``. The user environment (usually ``os.environ`` in Python)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:894
msgid ""
"``hostname``. The hostname of the system (if ``hostname`` is an executable "
"in the user's PATH)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:898
msgid "SpecLists as Constraints"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:900
msgid ""
"Dependencies and compilers in Spack can be both packages in an environment "
"and constraints on other packages. References to SpecLists allow a shorthand "
"to treat packages in a list as either a compiler or a dependency using the "
"``$%`` or ``$^`` syntax respectively."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:903
msgid ""
"For example, the following environment has three root packages: "
"``gcc@8.1.0``, ``mvapich2@2.3.1 %gcc@8.1.0``, and ``hdf5+mpi %gcc@8.1.0 "
"^mvapich2@2.3.1``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:905
msgid ""
"spack:\n"
"  definitions:\n"
"  - compilers: [gcc@8.1.0]\n"
"  - mpis: [mvapich2@2.3.1]\n"
"  - packages: [hdf5+mpi]\n"
"\n"
"  specs:\n"
"  - $compilers\n"
"  - matrix:\n"
"    - [$mpis]\n"
"    - [$%compilers]\n"
"  - matrix:\n"
"    - [$packages]\n"
"    - [$^mpis]\n"
"    - [$%compilers]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:923
msgid ""
"This allows for a much-needed reduction in redundancy between packages and "
"constraints."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:928
msgid "Spec Groups"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:932
msgid ""
"Environments can be organized with named spec groups, enabling you to apply "
"localized configuration overrides and establish concretization dependencies. "
"This is extremely useful in a couple of common scenarios, as detailed below."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:938
msgid "Building and using a compiler in a single environment"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:940
msgid ""
"A common use case is to build a recent compiler on top of an existing system "
"and then compile a stack of software with it. For instance, assume we are "
"interested in building ``hdf5`` and ``libtree`` with ``gcc@15.2``. The "
"following manifest file would do exactly that:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:944
msgid ""
"spack:\n"
"  specs:\n"
"  - group: compiler\n"
"    specs:\n"
"    - gcc@15.2\n"
"\n"
"  - group: apps\n"
"    needs: [compiler]\n"
"    specs:\n"
"    - hdf5 %gcc@15.2\n"
"    - libtree %gcc@15.2"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:958
msgid ""
"The ``group:`` attribute allows to name a group of specs, which are then "
"listed under the ``specs:`` attribute in the same object. The simplest "
"example is the ``compiler`` group composed of just the ``gcc@15.2`` spec."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:961
msgid ""
"To express dependencies among groups of specs the ``needs:`` attribute is "
"used, which is a list of names corresponding to the groups we depend on. The "
"way this works is that group dependencies are always concretized *before* "
"the current group, and their specs are *always* available for reuse when the "
"current group is concretized."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:967
msgid "Configuring a group of specs"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:969
msgid ""
"Another common scenario is the deployment of different configurations (e.g. "
"CUDA enabled vs. ROCm enabled) of the same set of software. As an example, "
"assume we want to install ``gromacs`` and ``quantum-espresso`` for both "
"``target=x86_64_v3`` and ``target=x86_64_v4``. That can be done with the "
"following manifest file:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:974
msgid ""
"spack:\n"
"- group: apps-x86_64_v3\n"
"  specs:\n"
"  - gromacs\n"
"  - quantum-espresso\n"
"  override:\n"
"    packages:\n"
"      all:\n"
"        prefer:\n"
"        - target=x86_64_v3\n"
"\n"
"- group: apps-x86_64_v4\n"
"  specs:\n"
"  - gromacs\n"
"  - quantum-espresso\n"
"  override:\n"
"    packages:\n"
"      all:\n"
"        prefer:\n"
"        - target=x86_64_v4"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:997
msgid ""
"The ``override:`` attribute allows us to override the configuration for a "
"single group of specs. The overridden part is always added as the *topmost* "
"scope when the current group is concretized. This ensures the override "
"always takes precedence over other sources of configuration."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1004
msgid "Controlling garbage collection with ``explicit: false``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1006
msgid ""
"By default every spec group is treated as a set of *explicit* roots. This "
"means its specs are preserved by ``spack gc`` even when nothing else depends "
"on them. Setting ``explicit: false`` on a group marks its specs as "
"*implicit*, making them eligible for garbage collection once no other "
"installed spec depends on them:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1010
msgid ""
"spack:\n"
"  specs:\n"
"  - group: compiler\n"
"    explicit: false\n"
"    specs:\n"
"    - gcc@15.2\n"
"\n"
"  - group: apps\n"
"    needs: [compiler]\n"
"    specs:\n"
"    - hdf5 %gcc@15.2\n"
"    - libtree %gcc@15.2"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1025
msgid ""
"After the apps are installed, ``spack gc`` will remove the compiler once no "
"installed spec has a link or run dependency on it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1029
msgid ""
"Flipping ``explicit: false`` on a group that has already been installed does "
"**not** retroactively update the database record for the already-installed "
"specs. The flag takes effect only for specs installed, or re-installed, "
"after the change. To immediately mark an existing spec as implicit, use "
"``spack mark -i <spec>``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1035
msgid "Modifying Environment Variables"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1037
msgid ""
"Spack Environments can modify the active shell's environment variables when "
"activated. The environment can be configured to set, unset, prepend, or "
"append using ``env_vars`` configuration in ``spack.yaml``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1040
msgid ""
"spack:\n"
"  env_vars:\n"
"    set:\n"
"      ENVAR_TO_SET_IN_ENV_LOAD: \"FOO\"\n"
"    unset:\n"
"    - ENVAR_TO_UNSET_IN_ENV_LOAD\n"
"    prepend_path:\n"
"      PATH_LIST: \"path/to/prepend\"\n"
"    append_path:\n"
"      PATH_LIST: \"path/to/append\"\n"
"    remove_path:\n"
"      PATH_LIST: \"path/to/remove\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1056
msgid "Environment Views"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1058
msgid ""
"Spack Environments can have an associated filesystem view, which is a "
"directory with a more traditional structure ``<view>/bin``, ``<view>/lib``, "
"``<view>/include`` in which all files of the installed packages are linked."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1060
msgid ""
"By default a view is created for each environment, thanks to the ``view: "
"true`` option in the ``spack.yaml`` manifest file:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1062
msgid ""
"spack:\n"
"  specs: [perl, python]\n"
"  view: true"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1068
msgid ""
"The view is created in a hidden directory ``.spack-env/view`` relative to "
"the environment. If you've used ``spack env activate``, you may have already "
"interacted with this view. Spack prepends its ``<view>/bin`` dir to ``PATH`` "
"when the environment is activated, so that you can directly run executables "
"from all installed packages in the environment."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1072
msgid ""
"Views are highly customizable: you can control where they are put, modify "
"their structure, include and exclude specs, change how files are linked, and "
"you can even generate multiple views for a single environment."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1077
msgid "Minimal view configuration"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1079
msgid "The minimal configuration"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1081
msgid ""
"spack:\n"
"  # ...\n"
"  view: true"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1087
msgid ""
"lets Spack generate a single view with default settings under the ``.spack-"
"env/view`` directory of the environment."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1089
msgid ""
"Another short way to configure a view is to specify just where to put it:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1091
msgid ""
"spack:\n"
"  # ...\n"
"  view: /path/to/view"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1097
msgid "Views can also be disabled by setting ``view: false``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1102
msgid "Advanced view configuration"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1104
msgid ""
"One or more **view descriptors** can be defined under ``view``, keyed by a "
"name. The example from the previous section with ``view: /path/to/view`` is "
"equivalent to defining a view descriptor named ``default`` with a ``root`` "
"attribute:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1107
msgid ""
"spack:\n"
"  # ...\n"
"  view:\n"
"    default:  # name of the view\n"
"      root: /path/to/view  # view descriptor attribute"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1115
msgid ""
"The ``default`` view descriptor name is special: when you ``spack env "
"activate`` your environment, this view will be used to update (among other "
"things) your ``PATH`` variable."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1117
msgid ""
"View descriptors must contain the root of the view, and optionally "
"projections, ``select`` and ``exclude`` lists and link information via "
"``link`` and ``link_type``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1119
msgid ""
"As a more advanced example, in the following manifest file snippet we define "
"a view named ``mpis``, rooted at ``/path/to/view`` in which all projections "
"use the package name, version, and compiler name to determine the path for a "
"given package. This view selects all packages that depend on MPI, and "
"excludes those built with the GCC compiler at version 8.5. The root specs "
"with their (transitive) link and run type dependencies will be put in the "
"view due to the  ``link: all`` option, and the files in the view will be "
"symlinks to the Spack install directories."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1123
msgid ""
"spack:\n"
"  # ...\n"
"  view:\n"
"    mpis:\n"
"      root: /path/to/view\n"
"      select: [^mpi]\n"
"      exclude: [\"%gcc@8.5\"]\n"
"      projections:\n"
"        all: \"{name}/{version}-{compiler.name}\"\n"
"      link: all\n"
"      link_type: symlink\n"
"      link_dirs: true"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1138
msgid ""
"The default for the ``select`` and ``exclude`` values is to select "
"everything and exclude nothing. The default projection is the default view "
"projection (``{}``). The ``link`` attribute allows the following values:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1142
msgid ""
"``link: all`` include root specs with their transitive run and link type "
"dependencies (default);"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1143
msgid ""
"``link: run`` include root specs with their transitive run type dependencies;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1144
msgid "``link: roots`` include root specs without their dependencies."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1146
msgid ""
"The ``link_type`` defaults to ``symlink`` but can also take the value of "
"``hardlink`` or ``copy``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1150
msgid ""
"The ``link_dirs`` option controls whether directories are symlinked. This is "
"the default behavior in Spack v1.2 and later. This is an optimization that "
"significantly reduces the time to create views, and reduces the inode usage "
"of the view. It only applies when ``link_type`` is set to ``symlink``. If "
"you want to link only non-directory files, set ``link_dirs: false``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1157
msgid ""
"The option ``link: run`` can be used to create small environment views for "
"Python packages. Python will be able to import packages *inside* of the view "
"even when the environment is not activated, and linked libraries will be "
"located *outside* of the view thanks to rpaths."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1160
msgid ""
"From the command line, the ``spack env create`` command takes an argument "
"``--with-view [PATH]`` that sets the path for a single, default view. If no "
"path is specified, the default path is used (``view: true``). The argument "
"``--without-view`` can be used to create an environment without any view "
"configured."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1164
msgid ""
"The ``spack env view`` command can be used to manage views of an "
"environment. The subcommand ``spack env view enable`` will add a view named "
"``default`` to an environment. It takes an optional argument to specify the "
"path for the new default view. The subcommand ``spack env view disable`` "
"will remove the view named ``default`` from an environment if one exists. "
"The subcommand ``spack env view regenerate`` will regenerate the views for "
"the environment. This will apply any updates in the environment "
"configuration that have not yet been applied."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1174
msgid "View Projections"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1175
msgid ""
"The default projection into a view is to link every package into the root of "
"the view. The projections attribute is a mapping of partial specs to spec "
"format strings, defined by the :meth:`~spack.spec.Spec.format` function, as "
"shown in the example below:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1178
msgid ""
"projections:\n"
"  zlib: \"{name}-{version}\"\n"
"  ^mpi: \"{name}-{version}/{^mpi.name}-{^mpi.version}-{compiler.name}-"
"{compiler.version}\"\n"
"  all: \"{name}-{version}/{compiler.name}-{compiler.version}\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1185
msgid ""
"Projections also permit environment and Spack configuration variable "
"expansions as shown below:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1187
msgid ""
"projections:\n"
"  all: \"{name}-{version}/{compiler.name}-{compiler.version}/$date/"
"$SYSTEM_ENV_VARIABLE\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1192
msgid ""
"where ``$date`` is the Spack configuration variable that will expand with "
"the ``YYYY-MM-DD`` format and ``$SYSTEM_ENV_VARIABLE`` is an environment "
"variable defined in the shell."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1194
msgid ""
"The entries in the projections configuration file must all be either specs "
"or the keyword ``all``. For each spec, the projection used will be the first "
"non-``all`` entry that the spec satisfies, or ``all`` if there is an entry "
"for ``all`` and no other entry is satisfied by the spec. Where the keyword "
"``all`` appears in the file does not matter."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1198
msgid ""
"Given the example above, the spec ``zlib@1.2.8`` will be linked into ``/my/"
"view/zlib-1.2.8/``, the spec ``hdf5@1.8.10+mpi %gcc@4.9.3 ^mvapich2@2.2`` "
"will be linked into ``/my/view/hdf5-1.8.10/mvapich2-2.2-gcc-4.9.3``, and the "
"spec ``hdf5@1.8.10~mpi %gcc@4.9.3`` will be linked into ``/my/view/"
"hdf5-1.8.10/gcc-4.9.3``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1200
msgid ""
"If the keyword ``all`` does not appear in the projections configuration "
"file, any spec that does not satisfy any entry in the file will be linked "
"into the root of the view as in a single-prefix view. Any entries that "
"appear below the keyword ``all`` in the projections configuration file will "
"not be used, as all specs will use the projection under ``all`` before "
"reaching those entries."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1204
msgid "Group of Specs"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1206
msgid ""
"Views can also be applied to a selected list of :ref:`spec groups "
"<environment-spec-matrices>`. This can be done by specifying the ``group:`` "
"attribute in the view configuration. For instance, with the following "
"manifest:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1210
msgid ""
"spack:\n"
"  concretizer:\n"
"    unify: true\n"
"\n"
"  packages:\n"
"    all:\n"
"      require:\n"
"      - target=x86_64_v4\n"
"\n"
"  specs:\n"
"  - group: compiler\n"
"    specs:\n"
"    - gcc@15.2\n"
"\n"
"  - group: apps\n"
"    needs: [compiler]\n"
"    specs:\n"
"    - hdf5~mpi %gcc@15.2\n"
"    - libtree %gcc@15.2\n"
"\n"
"  view:\n"
"    apps:\n"
"      root: ./views/apps\n"
"      group: apps"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1237
msgid ""
"The view will only contain entries from the ``apps`` group, and will not "
"include specs from the ``compiler`` group."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1240
msgid "Activating environment views"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1242
msgid "The ``spack env activate <env>`` command has two effects:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1244
msgid ""
"It activates the environment so that further Spack commands such as ``spack "
"install`` will run in the context of the environment."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1245
msgid ""
"It activates the view so that environment variables such as ``PATH`` are "
"updated to include the view."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1247
msgid ""
"Without further arguments, the ``default`` view of the environment is "
"activated. If a view with a different name has to be activated, ``spack env "
"activate --with-view <name> <env>`` can be used instead. You can also "
"activate the environment without modifying further environment variables "
"using ``--without-view``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1251
msgid ""
"The environment variables affected by the ``spack env activate`` command and "
"the paths that are used to update them are determined by the :ref:`prefix "
"inspections <customize-env-modifications>` defined in your modules "
"configuration; the defaults are summarized in the following table."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1254
msgid "Variable"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1254
msgid "Paths"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1256
msgid "PATH"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1256
msgid "bin"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1257
msgid "MANPATH"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1257
msgid "man, share/man"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1258
msgid "ACLOCAL_PATH"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1258
msgid "share/aclocal"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1259
msgid "PKG_CONFIG_PATH"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1259
msgid "lib/pkgconfig, lib64/pkgconfig, share/pkgconfig"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1260
msgid "CMAKE_PREFIX_PATH"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1260
msgid "."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1263
msgid ""
"Each of these paths are appended to the view root, and added to the relevant "
"variable if the path exists. For this reason, it is not recommended to use "
"non-default projections with the default view of an environment."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1266
msgid ""
"The ``spack env deactivate`` command will remove the active view of the "
"Spack environment from the user's environment variables."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1273
msgid "Generating Depfiles from Environments"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1275
msgid ""
"Spack can generate ``Makefile``\\s to make it easier to build multiple "
"packages in an environment in parallel."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1279
msgid ""
"Since Spack v1.1, there is a new experimental installer that supports "
"package-level parallelism out of the box with POSIX jobserver support. You "
"can enable it with ``spack config add config:installer:new``. This new "
"installer may provide a simpler alternative to the ``spack env depfile`` "
"workflow described in this section for users primarily interested in "
"speeding up environment installations."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1283
msgid ""
"Generated ``Makefile``\\s expose targets that can be included in existing "
"``Makefile``\\s, to allow other targets to depend on the environment "
"installation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1285
msgid "A typical workflow is as follows:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1287
msgid ""
"$ spack env create -d .\n"
"$ spack -e . add perl\n"
"$ spack -e . concretize\n"
"$ spack -e . env depfile -o Makefile\n"
"$ make -j64"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1295
msgid ""
"This generates a ``Makefile`` from a concretized environment in the current "
"working directory, and ``make -j64`` installs the environment, exploiting "
"parallelism across packages as much as possible. Spack respects the Make "
"jobserver and forwards it to the build environment of packages, meaning that "
"a single ``-j`` flag is enough to control the load, even when packages are "
"built in parallel."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1298
msgid "By default the following phony convenience targets are available:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1300
msgid "``make all``: installs the environment (default target);"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1301
msgid ""
"``make clean``: cleans files used by make, but does not uninstall packages."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1305
msgid ""
"GNU Make version 4.3 and above have great support for output synchronization "
"through the ``-O`` and ``--output-sync`` flags, which ensure that output is "
"printed orderly per package install. To get synchronized output with colors, "
"use ``make -j<N> SPACK_COLOR=always --output-sync=recurse``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1309
msgid "Specifying dependencies on generated ``make`` targets"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1311
msgid ""
"An interesting question is how to include generated ``Makefile``\\s in your "
"own ``Makefile``\\s. This comes up when you want to install an environment "
"that provides executables required in a command for a make target of your "
"own."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1314
msgid ""
"The example below shows how to accomplish this: the ``env`` target specifies "
"the generated ``spack/env`` target as a prerequisite, meaning that the "
"environment gets installed and is available for use in the ``env`` target."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1316
msgid ""
"SPACK ?= spack\n"
"\n"
".PHONY: all clean env\n"
"\n"
"all: env\n"
"\n"
"spack.lock: spack.yaml\n"
"\t$(SPACK) -e . concretize -f\n"
"\n"
"env.mk: spack.lock\n"
"\t$(SPACK) -e . env depfile -o $@ --make-prefix spack\n"
"\n"
"env: spack/env\n"
"\t$(info environment installed!)\n"
"\n"
"clean:\n"
"\trm -rf spack.lock env.mk spack/\n"
"\n"
"ifeq (,$(filter clean,$(MAKECMDGOALS)))\n"
"include env.mk\n"
"endif"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1340
msgid ""
"This works as follows: when ``make`` is invoked, it first \"remakes\" the "
"missing include ``env.mk`` as there is a target for it. This triggers "
"concretization of the environment and makes Spack output ``env.mk``. At that "
"point the generated target ``spack/env`` becomes available through ``include "
"env.mk``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1344
msgid ""
"As it is typically undesirable to remake ``env.mk`` as part of ``make "
"clean``, the include is conditional."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1348
msgid ""
"When including generated ``Makefile``\\s, it is important to use the ``--"
"make-prefix`` flag and use the non-phony target ``<prefix>/env`` as "
"prerequisite, instead of the phony target ``<prefix>/all``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1351
msgid "Building a subset of the environment"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1353
msgid ""
"The generated ``Makefile``\\s contain install targets for each spec, "
"identified by ``<name>-<version>-<hash>``. This allows you to install only a "
"subset of the packages in the environment. When packages are unique in the "
"environment, it's enough to know the name and let tab-completion fill out "
"the version and hash."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1357
msgid ""
"The following phony targets are available: ``install/<spec>`` to install the "
"spec with its dependencies, and ``install-deps/<spec>`` to *only* install "
"its dependencies. This can be useful when certain flags should only apply to "
"dependencies. Below we show a use case where a spec is installed with "
"verbose output (``spack install --verbose``) while its dependencies are "
"installed silently:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1361
msgid ""
"$ spack env depfile -o Makefile\n"
"\n"
"# Install dependencies in parallel, only show a log on error.\n"
"$ make -j16 install-deps/python-3.11.0-<hash> SPACK_INSTALL_FLAGS=--show-log-"
"on-error\n"
"\n"
"# Install the root spec with verbose output.\n"
"$ make -j16 install/python-3.11.0-<hash> SPACK_INSTALL_FLAGS=--verbose"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1372
msgid "Adding post-install hooks"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1374
msgid ""
"Another advanced use-case of generated ``Makefile``\\s is running a post-"
"install command for each package. These \"hooks\" could be anything from "
"printing a post-install message, running tests, or pushing just-built "
"binaries to a build cache."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1377
msgid ""
"This can be accomplished through the generated "
"``[<prefix>/]SPACK_PACKAGE_IDS`` variable. Assuming we have an active and "
"concrete environment, we generate the associated ``Makefile`` with a prefix "
"``example``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1380
msgid "$ spack env depfile -o env.mk --make-prefix example"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1384
msgid ""
"And we now include it in a different ``Makefile``, in which we create a "
"target ``example/push/%`` with ``%`` referring to a package identifier. This "
"target depends on the particular package installation. In this target we "
"automatically have the target-specific ``HASH`` and ``SPEC`` variables at "
"our disposal. They are respectively the spec hash (excluding leading ``/``), "
"and a human-readable spec. Finally, we have an entry point target ``push`` "
"that will update the build cache index once every package is pushed. Note "
"how this target uses the generated ``example/SPACK_PACKAGE_IDS`` variable to "
"define its prerequisites."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../environments.rst:1391
msgid ""
"SPACK ?= spack\n"
"BUILDCACHE_DIR = $(CURDIR)/tarballs\n"
"\n"
".PHONY: all\n"
"\n"
"all: push\n"
"\n"
"include env.mk\n"
"\n"
"example/push/%: example/install/%\n"
"\t@mkdir -p $(dir $@)\n"
"\t$(info About to push $(SPEC) to a buildcache)\n"
"\t$(SPACK) -e . buildcache push --only=package $(BUILDCACHE_DIR) /$(HASH)\n"
"\t@touch $@\n"
"\n"
"push: $(addprefix example/push/,$(example/SPACK_PACKAGE_IDS))\n"
"\t$(info Updating the buildcache index)\n"
"\t$(SPACK) -e . buildcache update-index $(BUILDCACHE_DIR)\n"
"\t$(info Done!)\n"
"\t@touch $@"
msgstr ""
